In [19]:
# b) There are 10 blocks per day for our dataset so blocks 1-10 will have timestamp
# 01-01-2018, while blocks 3641 - 3650 will have time-stamp 12/31/2018
import radar
import datetime
timestamp=[]
#generate sequential 10 copies per day between 01-01-2018 and 31-12-2018 x
for x in range(10000):
    timestamp.append(radar.random_datetime(
        start = datetime.datetime(year=2018, month=1, day=1),
        stop = datetime.datetime(year=2019, month=1, day=1)))
In [20]:
start = datetime.datetime.strptime("01-01-2018", "%d-%m-%Y")
end = datetime.datetime.strptime("01-01-2019", "%d-%m-%Y")
date_generated = [start + datetime.timedelta(days=x) for x in range(0, (end-start).days)]

import datetime
dates = []
def last_day_of_month(any_day):
    next_month = any_day.replace(day=28) + datetime.timedelta(days=4)
    return next_month - datetime.timedelta(days=next_month.day)
for month in range(1, 13):
    dates.append(last_day_of_month(datetime.date(2018, month, 1)))

2) Pick any two blockchains from https://coinmetrics.io/data-downloads/ and download their aggregate on-chain dataset (offerred in csv format) and produce an interesting visualization from the data. Feel free to use your imagination and dont be restricted to just standard plots (bar, line, histogram etc). The goal is to display the data in a way such that the viewer can distinctly take away an insight from the dataset.

Ideally, it would have been great to conduct a Principal Component Analysis for dimensionality reduction. However, over 95% of the variance is held by one component, due to high price-marketCap correlation and independnce of the rest of the features. A multi-dimensional visualizaion comprising of the principal components would have been interesting to interpret.
